  "prompt": "What's a good moveset for Lycanroc in Pokemon Sun and Moon?",
  "response": "Okay, let's craft a good moveset for Lycanroc in Pokemon Sun and Moon, keeping in mind the different forms (Midday, Midnight, and Dusk) and the general competitive landscape of the game.\n\n**General Considerations**\n\n*   **Nature and Ability:** The best natures for Lycanroc are **Adamant** (attack up, special attack down) or **Jolly** (speed up, special attack down). Adamant is good for more power while Jolly gives it a better chance to move first.\n    *   **Midday Form:**  **Sand Rush** is the most viable ability, boosting speed in sand.  **Keen Eye** and **Steadfast** are underwhelming.\n    *   **Midnight Form:** **No Guard** is the most useful ability allowing for the always-accurate Stone Edge.  **Keen Eye** and **Steadfast** are underwhelming.\n    *   **Dusk Form:** **Tough Claws** is the most powerful ability, boosting contact moves by 30%.\n\n*   **Held Item:**\n\n    *   **Life Orb:**  Increases damage output at the cost of some HP per attack. Good for maximizing offensive pressure.\n    *   **Choice Band:**  Greatly boosts attack, but locks you into one move. Ideal for a hit-and-run strategy.\n    *   **Focus Sash:** Allows it to survive one hit at 1 HP. Good if you need to get off one important move.\n\n**Midday Form Moveset (Sand Rush)**\n\n*   This set relies on having a Sandstorm setter on your team (e.g., Hippowdon or Tyranitar).\n\n    1.  **Stone Edge:**  High power, STAB (Same-Type Attack Bonus).  A powerful Rock-type attack.\n    2.  **Accelerock:**  Priority Rock-type move, allowing Lycanroc to move first in many situations.  Very important for picking off weakened opponents.\n    3.  **Close Combat:**  Powerful Fighting-type coverage move.  Hits Steel, Rock, Ice, and Dark types hard.  Lowers Defense and Special Defense.\n    4.  **Crunch / Drill Run:** Coverage Option.  Crunch hits Ghost and Psychic types, Drill Run hits Steel, Rock, and Electric.\n\n**Midday Form Explanation**\n\n*   This set is straightforward: Get sand up, and sweep with boosted Speed and strong STAB moves.  Accelerock is crucial for finishing off weakened foes.  Close Combat gives it excellent coverage. The last move is down to preference, depending on your team's needs.\n\n**Midnight Form Moveset (No Guard)**\n\n*   The main draw here is Stone Edge hitting 100% of the time.\n\n    1.  **Stone Edge:** High power, STAB (Same-Type Attack Bonus). With No Guard, it always hits.\n    2.  **Close Combat:**  Powerful Fighting-type coverage move.  Hits Steel, Rock, Ice, and Dark types hard.  Lowers Defense and Special Defense.\n    3.  **Sucker Punch:**  Priority Dark-type move.  Allows it to hit faster opponents or revenge kill.\n    4.  **Fire Punch / Thunder Punch / Iron Tail:** Coverage Option. Fire Punch is useful against Steel, Iron Tail against Fairy, Thunder Punch against Water and Flying.\n\n**Midnight Form Explanation**\n\n*   No Guard Stone Edge is the main selling point of this form. Close Combat handles many of the weaknesses. Sucker Punch is for priority and revenge killing, and the last move is a flexible coverage option.\n\n**Dusk Form Moveset (Tough Claws)**\n\n*   Dusk Form has the most potential due to Tough Claws boosting its contact moves.\n\n    1.  **Stone Edge:**  High power, STAB (Same-Type Attack Bonus). Still a great move.\n    2.  **Accelerock:**  Priority Rock-type move, boosted by Tough Claws.  Allows Lycanroc to move first in many situations and picking off weakened opponents.\n    3.  **Close Combat:**  Powerful Fighting-type coverage move.  Hits Steel, Rock, Ice, and Dark types hard.  Lowers Defense and Special Defense.\n    4.  **Crunch / Drill Run:** Coverage Option, also boosted by Tough Claws.  Crunch hits Ghost and Psychic types, Drill Run hits Steel, Rock, and Electric.\n\n**Dusk Form Explanation**\n\n*   This is the best Lycanroc variant for offensive pressure. Tough Claws boosts Accelerock and the coverage move. Stone Edge and Close Combat provide powerful STAB and coverage options.\n\n**General Tips for Using Lycanroc**\n\n*   **Scouting:** Be careful when switching in Lycanroc, especially if you expect a Ground or Water-type attack (a 4x weakness). Use a defensive pivot or scout with a move like U-Turn if possible.\n*   **Status Conditions:**  Avoid burns and paralysis, as they will cripple Lycanroc's offensive potential.\n*   **Team Synergy:**  Make sure your team covers Lycanroc's weaknesses. Good teammates include those that can handle Ground, Water, and Grass types.\n\n**Example Team Compositions (Just Ideas)**\n\n*   **Sand Team (Midday):**  Hippowdon/Tyranitar (Sand Setter), Lycanroc, Excadrill, Ferrothorn, Toxapex, Tapu Koko\n*   **Bulky Offense (Midnight):**  Lycanroc, Celesteela, Tapu Fini, Heatran, Garchomp, Magnezone\n*   **Balanced Offense (Dusk):**  Lycanroc, Greninja, Tapu Koko, Landorus-Therian, Ferrothorn, Toxapex\n\nUltimately, the best moveset and strategy for Lycanroc will depend on your team composition and the specific threats you expect to face. Consider your team's needs and experiment to find what works best! Good luck!\n",
